<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT. IV.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE I, The Hou&s;e of the Widow WARREN,</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>JENNY</HI> followed by <HI>Harry Dornton,</HI> who with an oppre&s;&s;ed heart, but half drunk with wine and pa&s;&s;ion, a&s;&s;umes the appearance of wild and exce&s;&s;ive gaiety.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HARRY.</SPEAKER>
<P>A WAY, Handmaid of Hecate! Fly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jenny.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, &s;ir, you don't mean as you &s;ay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you begone, Cerberea?&mdash;Invite my Godde&s;s to de&s;cend in a golden &s;hower, and &s;uddently relieve the&s;e racking doubts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Godde&s;s!&mdash;I knew you meant mi&s;s Sophy!</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Prime tormentrix to the Furies, begone!</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen,</SPEAKER>
<Q>What, &s;ir, to my old Mi&s;tre&s;s?</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Hear you?&mdash;Yes! I want an old Mi&s;tre&s;s, with her old gold, in&s;tantly to relieve an injured old man&mdash;Tol de rol&mdash;Vani&s;h, daughter of Nox! Tell her what a gay and love &s;ick humour I am in&mdash;Tol de rol.</Q>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>WIDOW,</HI> and Exit <HI>JENNY</HI> di&s;&s;atisfied.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Smiling]</STAGE> Mr. Dornton!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Widow!&mdash;Here am I!&mdash;Phaeton the &s;econd hurl|ed from my flaming car! I come burning with fierce de|&s;ires, devoutly bent on committing the deadly &s;in of ma|trimony! May the&s;e things be? Speak, my &s;aving Angel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Fie upon you! How can you throw one into &s;uch in&s;uperable trepidation of &s;pirits?</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Will you have me?&mdash;Pronounce but the ble&s;&s;ed Yes, and I am thine for ever and for aye.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Dear Mr Dornton&mdash;! You&mdash;I&mdash;</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Ay, ay&mdash;I know very well&mdash;The formal No, the crim&s;on blu&s;h, the half-con&s;enting &s;ide-glance, the
<PB N="51" REF="50">
he&s;itating Yes, the palpitation violent&mdash;We'll &s;uppo&s;e them all&mdash;There, there!&mdash;I have acted them over, and par&s;on's tragical farce is going to begin!</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but&mdash;! Dear Mr Dornton&mdash;!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not imagine, amiable widow, that I am mad!&mdash;No, no, no!&mdash; <STAGE>[With a hy&s;teric laugh]</STAGE> Only a little flighty&mdash;Left my father furiou&s;ly, drank three bottles of Burgundy franticly, flew in amorous phren&s;y to the at|tack, and will carry the place or die on the &s;pot!&mdash;Pow|der and poi&s;on await my choice; and let me tell you, &s;weet widow, I am a man of my word. So you'll have me, won't you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Mr Dornton&mdash;!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you would not &s;ee my father peri&s;h! Would you? And me expire! Would you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Am I &s;o very cruel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;ay Yes!&mdash;Yes or&mdash;Pi&s;tols&mdash;Daggers&mdash;Cannon balls!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, yes, yes!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, fair widow! Kind widow, hold! Be not ra&s;h!&mdash;I am the verie&s;t! villain!&mdash;Avoid me!&mdash;A ruined&mdash;! But that were indeed a trifle&mdash;My father! Him! Him have I ruined! Heard you that? Bring forth your hoards! Let him once more be him&s;elf, and bid me ki&s;s the du&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> <Q>Elegant youth! <STAGE>[Aloud]</STAGE> Ah you flatterer! I own you have been a little&mdash;wild, but&mdash;</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<Q>A little! Oh! Ha, ha, ha! Widow. I am a &s;ad fellow!&mdash;A damned &s;ad dog!&mdash;I tell you I have ruined my father&mdash;A prince of fathers! Who, had I not been a ra&s;cal, would have given me his &s;oul! And I have ruined him!&mdash;Ruined him!&mdash;Beware of me!&mdash;Fly me!&mdash;Yet &s;hould you?&mdash;Ri&s;e Imps of night! Deep have I &s;worn to find &s;ome means to &s;ave a father from de&s;truction, and I will keep my oath though&mdash;!</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh fie! How can you terrify one &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>And wilt thou, widow, be his &s;upport? <STAGE>[Eagerly]</STAGE> Wilt thou?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cruel que&s;tion! How can I deny?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Immortal ble&s;&s;ings be upon thee! My father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will be all rapture to hear&mdash;!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Will he?&mdash;Words of comfort!&mdash;Will he?&mdash;A buxom, fair and bounteous dame, who&s;e trea&s;ures
<PB N="52" REF="51">
can re&s;tore his tottering fortunes to their wonted &s;plen|dour! Ha! Will he? Will he?</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<Q>Certainly, Mr. Dornton, he cannot be di&s;|plea&s;ed at &s;uch a choice.</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Shakes his head]</STAGE> Ah, ha, ha, ha, <STAGE>[Sighs]</STAGE> You don't know my father! A &s;trange, affectionate&mdash;! That loves me&mdash;! Oh! He&mdash;! And you &s;ee how I u&s;e him! You &s;ee how I u&s;e him! But no matter&mdash;Tol de rol&mdash;We'll be married to-night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh fie!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, my Madona! To-night's the day&mdash;The &s;ooner the better&mdash;'Tis to re&s;cue a father, blith&s;ome widow! A father! To &s;ave him have I fallen in love&mdash;Remember&mdash;Sin with open eyes, widow&mdash;Money&mdash;I mu&s;t have money&mdash;Early in the morn, ere counters echo with the ring of gold, fifty thou&s;and mu&s;t be rai&s;ed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>It &s;hall, Mr. Dornton.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, &s;hall it? Shall it? Speak again, beatific vi&s;ion, &s;peak! Shall it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tol de rol&mdash;<Q>He &s;hall live! He &s;hall &s;mile! Again his heart &s;hall feel joy!&mdash;Oh my bland and bonny widow! <STAGE>[Partly &s;inging]</STAGE> My widow fair and debo|nair&mdash;Keep thy word&mdash;Let but my father be him&s;elf, and I am thine! Body and &s;oul thine!</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>And are your really&mdash;? Oh, no!&mdash;No&mdash; <STAGE>[Co|quetti&s;hly]</STAGE> You are not in love?</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<Q><L>Fathom and half, poor Tom!</L>
<L>And we'll love by day, and we'll live by night&mdash;</L>
<STAGE>[Singing and &s;ighing.</STAGE>
<L>With a hey and a ho and a heigho, widow!</L>
<L>I have drunk Burgundy&mdash;To your health, au&s;picious Amazon!&mdash;Burgundy!</L>
<LG>
<L>For I wanted the grace <STAGE>[Sings&punc;</STAGE></L>
<L>Of a bold villain's face,</L>
<L>To prevail, with heigho,</L>
<L>On a buxom widow. <STAGE>[Ki&s;&s;es her</STAGE></L>
</LG></Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q><STAGE>[Coquetting]</STAGE> Fie! I &s;hall hate you, if you are &s;o fond of me! I &s;hall indeed!&mdash;But no&mdash;You are man!&mdash;Roving faithle&s;s man!</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>No, no! Fear not! Thou, gracious widow, art my overflowing cup of con&s;olation&mdash;What! A fa|ther &s;aved&mdash;?</Q>&mdash;Remember!&mdash;Fifty thou&s;and the fir&s;t thing in the morning?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="53" REF="52">
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>And would not a part this evening&mdash;?</P>
<STAGE>[Still coquetting</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Suddenly]</STAGE> What &s;aye&s;t thou?&mdash;Oh, no!&mdash;Whoo!&mdash;Thou&s;ands&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>"No: you are a naughty bad man, and I don't love you: I don't indeed&mdash;El&s;e." I have a trifling &s;um.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Eagerly]</STAGE> How much?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Six thou&s;and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Six?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Which I meant to have di&s;po&s;ed of, but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no! I'll di&s;po&s;e of it, dear widow! <STAGE>[Ki&s;&s;es her]</STAGE> I'll di&s;po&s;e of it in a twinkling! <STAGE>[Elated]</STAGE> <Q>Thou&punc;art my Godde&s;s! <STAGE>[Ki&s;&s;es her again]</STAGE> By the faith of my body but I will thank thee&mdash;Yea thee will love ex|ceedingly!</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Oh fie!&mdash;No, you won't!&mdash;Will you?</Q></P>
<STAGE>[Langui&s;hingly.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Will I? <STAGE>[Sighs]</STAGE> Shall I not be in duty bound?</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>No!&mdash;You can love me.</Q></P>
<STAGE>[More fondly.]</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>Ha, ha, ha! My fair Pelican of Poto&s;i! Queen of Pactolus!</Q> Doubt not my gratitude&mdash;Let this and this&mdash; <STAGE>[Ki&s;&s;ing</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fie! You are a &s;ad man&mdash;But I'll bring you a draft!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do, my blooming widow! Empre&s;s of the gol|den i&s;les, do</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, you are a very bad man!&mdash;But re|member, this trifle is for your own u&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my pearl unparalleled! My father's! <Q>My father's! My pocket is an in&s;idious gulf, into which I never more will guineas ca&s;t.</Q> Save but my father, and I will ki&s;s the ground on which thou treade&s;t, and live and breathe but on thy bounty! <STAGE>[Self-indignation.]</STAGE></P>
<STAGE>[Exit Widow.</STAGE>
<L>At lea&s;t till time and fate &s;hall means afford</L>
<L>Somewhat to perform, worthy of man and me.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter JENNY peeping.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<P>St!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, ha! my merry maid of May!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e you are waiting to &s;ee mi&s;s Sophy, now you have got rid of the old lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har,</SPEAKER>
<P>Got rid of the old lady?&mdash;<Q>Thou brazen pin|placer, thou virgin of nine-and-twenty years occupa|tion!</Q> No. "I have not got rid of the old lady&punc;"
<PB N="54" REF="53">
The old lady is to be my blooming, youthful bride!&mdash;And I, happy youth, am written and de&s;tined in the records of eternity her other half!&mdash;"Before the &s;tars were this marriage was decreed&mdash;" Heigho.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jen.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, &s;ir, what rapturation,&mdash;But &s;tay a little, and I'll tell mi&s;s Sophy her mamma wants her, here; &s;o then&mdash;hu&s;h&mdash; <STAGE>[Jenny retires, making a &s;ign, and</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter the Widow Warren.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Widow.</SPEAKER>
<P>"An't you a &s;ad man?"&mdash;Here's the draft,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Harry.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thanks, my Sultana&mdash;<Q>Thou &s;hall find me very grateful&mdash;Thou ha&s;t bought and paid for me, and I am thine!&mdash;By fair and hone&s;t traffic thine!</Q>&mdash;This halcyon night the prie&s;t, pronouncing conjurations dire,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fie, I won't look at you:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, to-night we'll marry; &s;hall we not?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid,</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll not an&s;wer you a word! <STAGE>[Enter Sophia &s;kippingly, but &s;tops &s;hort,]</STAGE> "You are a dangerous man" <STAGE>[Sitting down and coquetting]</STAGE> how dare you talk to me of to-night?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>To-night &s;hall be a night of wonder, and we'll love like&mdash; <STAGE>[A&s;ide]</STAGE> like Darby and Joan,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Langui&s;hing]</STAGE> I &s;hall hate you intolerably!</P>
<STAGE>[Sophia advancing on tiptoe.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey for the par&s;on's permi&s;&s;ion, hay my &s;ub|lime widow,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;teal thus upon one at an unguarded mo|ment&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>But here fir&s;t let me kneel, and thus to Ceres pay <STAGE>[Going to ki&s;s her hand in rapture, meets the eye of Sophia,]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>"I'll never forgive you!&mdash;I hate you now wor&s;e than ever."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Coming between them with bur&s;ting trepida|tion, taking the valentine from her bo&s;om and pre&s;ent|ing it]</STAGE> there &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P>There &s;ir,&mdash;Oh pray &s;ir, take it &s;ir,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why minikin&mdash;I</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph</SPEAKER>
<P>I reque&s;t &s;ir,&mdash;I de&s;ire &s;ir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Declining it]</STAGE> Tol de rol,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Tearing the paper piecemeal, and throwing it &s;pitefully away]</STAGE> why then there, &s;ir&mdash;and there, &s;ir&mdash;and there, there, there, there, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor minikin! I declare, &s;he is jealous,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="54">
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Her &s;obs ri&s;ing]</STAGE> And I'll&mdash;I'll&mdash;wri-i-i-ite to my&mdash;to my grandma-a-a-a directly,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fie, child,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I'll go do-o-o-own&mdash;into Glo-o-o-o&s;ter|&s;hire,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go up to your chamber, child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I'll tell&punc;my grandma-a what a fal&s;e, ba&s;e, bad man you are: and &s;he &s;hall ha-ate you, and de&s;pi&s;e you; <Q>and every body &s;hall ha-ate you, and de&s;pi&s;e you;</Q> and I'll ha-a-ate you, and de&s;pi&s;e you my&s;elf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor thing!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P>And moreover I'll hate and de&s;pi&s;e all mankind and for your &s;ake <STAGE>[with great energy]</STAGE> I'll live and die a maid!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, child, that I dare be &s;worn you will,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Widow, I'm a &s;ad fellow, don't have me&mdash;I'm a vile fellow, Sophy! You are right to de&s;pi&s;e me, I am going to marry your mother!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll go down into Glo-o-o&s;ter&s;hire&mdash;I wo-on't live in &s;uch a fal&s;e-hearted city! And you ought to be a&s;hamed of your&s;elf, ma', to make your&s;elf &s;o ridi|culous.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, &s;weet Slyth, it is my fault, all my fault!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Enraged]</STAGE> Be gone, mi&s;s!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Interpo&s;ing]</STAGE> Sweet widow! gentle widow,&mdash;I've &s;old my&s;elf, Sophy, &s;ix thou&s;and pounds is the earne&s;t money paid down, for the reptile Harry Dornton&mdash;I love you, Sophy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Mr Dornton?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do by heaven! Take back your money, widow <STAGE>[Offering the draft]</STAGE> I'm a &s;ad &s;coundrel,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are a ba&s;e faithle&s;s man, you know you are, and you are a pitile&s;s woman, a mercile&s;s woman, for all you are my own mother, to let my poor brother Milford go to be &s;tarved to death in a dark dungeon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Milford in pri&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Soph.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, arre&s;ted by your cruel, old, ugly fa|ther, I'm &s;ure he is ugly! Though I never &s;aw him in my life, I'm &s;ure he is an ugly, hideous, ugly mon|&s;ter! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Har.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is this true, widow?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Wid.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Stammering]</STAGE> &s;ir&mdash;</P>
